    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-08-01T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-08-01T18:00:00-05:00" n="248"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d248">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.516 Export-Import Bank/7–1747: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Legation in Hungary</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-08-01T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 1, 1947—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>820. Board Directors <gloss target="#t_ExImBank1">Eximbank</gloss> Jul 31
                    considered cotton credit (<gloss target="#t_urtel1">urtels</gloss> 1195 Jul 17
                    and 1197 Jul 16<note n="1" xml:id="d248fn1">Telegram 1197, July 16, from
                        Budapest is printed on <ref target="#pg_336">p. 336</ref>; telegram 1195,
                        July 17, is not printed, but see footnote 1 to telegram 1197.</note>) and
                    decided to cancel credit for following reasons (1) at time credit negotiated
                    Hungarian Govt was under nominal control non-Communist Smallholders Parity.
                    Subsequent political coup changed complexion Govt and also resulted in exile
                    Hungarians who negotiated credit. While voluntary exile these persons does not
                    destroy legal validity agreement signed Apr 30 1947 Board <gloss
                        target="#t_ExImBank1">Eximbank</gloss> originally approved credit partly
                    because it had confidence in Hungarian negotiators who would also have
                    administered credit once it was in operation (2) the two Hungarian banks to
                    which credit extended are under threat nationalization and (3) info given <gloss
                        target="#t_ExImBank1">Eximbank</gloss> at time credit negotiated regarding
                    available supply sufficiently at variance with info contained <gloss
                        target="#t_urtel1">urtel</gloss> 1195 to warrant reconsideration credit.</p>
                <p>Since inquiry about status credit was raised in Budapest Bank and <gloss
                        target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> opinion that you should inform Govt regarding
                    cancellation.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> and Bank considering publicity and request
                    your comments regarding appropriate time and procedure to be followed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
